    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Segregation at the Bookstore</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Christopher Moore letter says bookstores that practice 'racial profiling' do disservice to black authors and book-buying public (Ward Connerly's May 8 Op-Ed)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Ward Connerly is right (Op-Ed, May 8) that Jim Crow is alive and well among American booksellers. Though as a black author who enjoys seeing his perennial, ''Santa &amp; Pete: A Novel of Christmas Present and Past,'' on bookstore shelves each holiday season, it is not uncommon for me, like Mr. Connerly, to have to  ask a sales manager to remove my book from the black studies section  to the far more appropriate Christmas book table or display.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Ward Connerly is right (Op-Ed, May 8) that Jim Crow is alive and well among American booksellers. Though as a black author who enjoys seeing his perennial, ''Santa &amp; Pete: A Novel of Christmas Present and Past,'' on bookstore shelves each holiday season, it is not uncommon for me, like Mr. Connerly, to have to  ask a sales manager to remove my book from the black studies section  to the far more appropriate Christmas book table or display.</p>
        <p>Indeed, ''racial profiling'' is a disservice to black authors and the book-buying public.</p>
        <p>CHRISTOPHER MOORE  Brooklyn, May 8, 2000</p>
      </block>
